T1  - THE EFFECTS OF FISCAL SHOCKS ON EMPLOYMENT AND THE REAL WAGE*
AU  - Pappa, Evi
Y1  - 2009/02/01
PY  - 2009
DA  - 2009/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2008.00528.x
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 217
EP  - 244
VL  - 50
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2008.00528.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - We study the transmission of fiscal shocks in the labor market. We employ a structural VAR and base identification on the restrictions that shocks to government consumption, investment, and employment must raise output and deficits. These restrictions hold in both prototype Real Business Cycle (RBC) and New Keynesian models. Shocks to government consumption and investment increase real wages and employment contemporaneously, both at state level and in the aggregate. The dynamics in response to employment shocks are mixed: Increases in government employment raise the real wage and total employment in the aggregate. However, in one third of the states they reduce total employment.
ER  - 

